groq_web_research.answer:
**1. Summary (non‑crypto meaning)**  
- **Kanta Mizuno** is the real name of the protagonist of the Japanese post‑apocalyptic manga & anime *Desert Punk* (original title 砂ぼうず, *Sunabōzu*).  
- He is a flamboyant, self‑styled “handyman” bounty‑hunter who roams the ruined “Grand Kanto” desert, taking on dangerous jobs for money.  
- The nickname **Sunabōzu** literally translates to “sand monk/​sand brat,” reflecting his gritty, survival‑ist persona in a world turned to endless desert.

**2. Origin / Timeline (non‑crypto)**  
- **1997** – *Desert Punk* (originally titled *Sunabōzu*) created by manga artist **Usune Masatoshi** and first serialized in *Comic Beam* (Enterbrain).  
- **2000** – The series gains a cult following for its dark humor and stark post‑apocalyptic setting.  
- **2005** – An anime adaptation produced by Gonzo airs, popularizing the character Kanta Mizuno (voiced by Chihiro Suzuki in Japanese, Eric Vale in English).  
- The term **Sunabōzu** has since entered niche otaku slang to describe a rugged, lone‑wolf survivor archetype, especially in discussions of post‑apocalyptic media.

**3. Sources**  
- [Desert Punk – Wikipedia (EN)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Desert_Punk) – overview of manga/anime, character name & nickname.  
- [Desert Punk – Wikipedia (PT)](https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Desert_Punk) – Portuguese version confirming original title *Sunabōzu* and Kanta Mizuno’s role.  

*These sources verify the cultural origin of “Kanta Mizuno” and the meaning of “Sunabōzu” outside any cryptocurrency context.*

**1) Summary**  
- “Fartcoin” draws on the everyday English word **fart**, a term for the emission of digestive gases that has long been used for humor and slap‑slap jokes.  
- In internet culture the word has been repurposed in a series of memes (e.g., “Doo Doo Fart,” the “Onara” fetish series, and the spoonerism “Smart Fella, Fart Smella”) that treat flatulence as a punch‑line or a bait‑and‑switch gag.  
- The token’s name therefore likely leverages this long‑standing comedic connotation rather than any technical or financial meaning.  

**2) Origin / Timeline**  
- **Middle English roots** – The word appears in Middle English forms *ferten*, *feortan*, *farten*, linked to Old High German *ferzan* and cognates in Old Norse, Slavic and Greek【https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fart_(word) - etymology of “fart”】.  
- **15th‑century usage** – Recorded as a noun/verb for flatulence in early English texts【https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wiktionary:fart - historical definition】.  
- **Early‑2000s meme emergence** – “Onara” (Japanese for “fart”) became a bait‑and‑switch flash meme on 4chan’s /f/ board, spreading the fetishized gag format【https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/subcultures/onara-fart-fetish - 4chan origin】.  
- **2010s‑2020s meme proliferation** – “Doo Doo Fart” (a distorted SpongeBob‑style clip) and the spoonerism “Smart Fella, Fart Smella” went viral on TikTok, Reddit and other platforms, cementing fart‑related humor in meme lexicon【https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/doo-doo-fart - viral video meme】, 【https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/smart-fella-fart-smella - 2021 viral spoonerism】.  

**3) Sources**  
- https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fart_(word) – etymology of “fart”  
- https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wiktionary:fart – historical definition  
- https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/doo-doo-fart – modern fart meme example  
- https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/subcultures/onara-fart-fetish – early 4chan fart meme series  
- https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/smart-fella-fart-smella – 2021 viral spoonerism meme

- **Tuna (Spanish/Portuguese university tradition):** A centuries‑old student musical group that dresses in traditional “tuna” garb, sings serenades, and travels between universities.  

**2. Origin / Timeline**  
- **Fish name:** Derived from Spanish *atún* ← Andalusian Arabic *at‑tūn* ← Classical Arabic *al‑tūn* ← Latin *thunnus* ← Ancient Greek *θύννος* (θύνω “to rush, dart”). The term has been used for the fish since antiquity.  
- **Student “tuna” groups:** Originated in 13th‑century Spain and Portugal as wandering university students who performed music for food or money. The tradition spread throughout Iberia and Latin America; modern “tunas” preserve the costume and repertoire for cultural and social reasons.  

**3. Sources**  
- **Fish etymology:** Wikipedia – “Tuna” (fish) – explains Arabic → Latin → Greek roots of the word. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tuna (covers name origin).

**Summary – non‑crypto meaning**

- The franchise includes picture‑book series (first published 1986) and an animated TV series (1997‑2004, later revived as *Franklin & Friends*).  
- Themes focus on friendship, school life, problem‑solving and family values; the character is known for his gentle, curious personality and catch‑phrase “I can count by twos and tie my shoes.”

**Origin / timeline**  
- **1986‑87** – Paulette Bourgeois writes the first *Franklin* book; Brenda Clark provides illustrations. The book *Franklin the Turtle* is released by Kids Can Press (Canada).  
- **1990s** – The series expands to over 30 titles, translated into many languages and selling tens of millions of copies worldwide.  
- **1997** – Nelvana produces the first animated TV series *Franklin* (aired on Canada’s Treehouse TV and later on U.S. Nick Jr./Noggin).  
- **2000‑2006** – Several direct‑to‑video specials and a feature film (*Franklin and the Green Knight*, *Franklin’s Magic Christmas*, etc.) are released.  
- **2011‑2013** – CGI reboot *Franklin & Friends* airs, introducing the character to a new generation.

**1. What it is** – Liquid Collective is a liquid‑staking protocol that pools users’ assets into a shared “collective” staking pool, letting participants earn staking rewards while retaining the ability to move their capital freely【1†https://x.com/nmvalera_】.  

**2. Where docs / whitepaper are** – All publicly‑available material lives on X (formerly Twitter):  

* Litepaper (overview of the protocol & liquid‑staking growth) – https://x.com/nmvalera_ (tweet announcing the “Liquid Collective Litepaper”)  
* Token‑omics discussion – https://x.com/mahsa_tin/status/1998279040663199932  
* 2024/2025 roadmap – https://x.com/Liquid_Start (Roadmap post)  

**3. Key features (as described on‑site)**  

- **Collective staking pool** – Users’ assets are combined into a single pool that stakes on multiple networks, increasing decentralisation and reducing individual minimums.  
- **Liquidity on‑demand** – Staked positions are represented by transferable tokens, allowing holders to sell or transfer their stake without waiting for unbonding periods.  
- **Governance token** – A native token (referenced in the token‑omics tweet) distributes rewards and grants voting rights over protocol upgrades.  
- **Cross‑chain support** – The litepaper mentions “growth of liquid staking” across several Layer‑1s, implying multi‑chain compatibility.  
- **Roadmap‑driven development** – The roadmap post outlines upcoming features such as “advanced risk‑management tools” and “integrations with major DeFi aggregators.”  

**4. Gaps / red‑flags**  

- **No dedicated documentation site** – All technical details are embedded in tweets; there is no searchable docs portal, API reference, or downloadable PDF linked directly.  
- **Missing audit reports** – No audit or security‑audit page is linked from the domain; the only security mention is a generic “smart‑contract audit” reminder in a third‑party tweet.  
- **Limited formal whitepaper** – The “litepaper” is announced but the actual PDF or full text is not directly accessible from the tweet, making thorough due‑diligence harder.

groq_web_research.answer:
**Cultural / non‑crypto meaning of “Wojak” (a.k.a. “Feels Guy”)**

- **What it is:** A simple MS‑Paint drawing of a bald, slightly hunched man with a forlorn expression. It is used as a “reaction‑face” meme to convey feelings such as loneliness, regret, melancholy, or existential dread. Over time it spawned countless variants (e.g., Doomer, Zoomer, Chad, Soyjak, Crying Wojak) that caricature different personality types or social groups.  
- **How it’s used:** Users paste the image into comment threads, imageboards, or social‑media posts to visually express a personal “feels” moment (“I know that feel, bro”) or to mock a situation. The meme’s flexibility comes from swapping captions, adding accessories, or pairing it with other meme characters (e.g., Pepe the Frog).  
- **Why it resonated:** The minimalist, relatable expression captures a universal sense of “being an outsider looking in,” making it a go‑to visual shorthand for self‑deprecating or empathetic commentary on internet culture.

**Origin & timeline (non‑crypto)**  

- **2009‑12‑16:** First known appearance on the humor site **SadAndUseless.com** as the “I Wish I Was at Home (They Don’t Know)” comic, showing Wojak standing alone at a party.  
- **2010‑2012:** Adopted on 4chan’s /r9k/ and /pol/ boards as “Feels Guy,” spreading rapidly as a reaction image for “I know that feel, bro.”  
- **2013‑2015:** Became a template for “Oomer” series (Boomer, Doomer, Zoomer, etc.) and for mash‑ups with other meme icons (Pepe x Wojak).  
- **2016‑present:** Continued diversification (Crying Wojak, Masked Wojak, Soyjak vs. Chad) and migration to mainstream platforms (Reddit, Twitter, TikTok), cementing its status as one of the internet’s longest‑running meme archetypes.

**Sources**  

1. **Know Your Meme – “Wojak”** – detailed history, earliest comic, and evolution of variants.  
   https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/wojak  
2. **Know Your Meme – “I Wish I Was at Home / They Don’t Know”** – explains the 2009 origin on SadAndUseless.com.  
   https://knowyourmeme.com/editorials/guides/where-does-the-they-dont-know-wojak-meme-come-from-how-to-use-the-i-wish-i-was-at-home-format-explained  

*(Both links were retrieved via targeted web searches limited to non‑crypto domains.)*

**1) Summary**  
- “6‑7” (or “67”) is an internet meme that originated from the lyric “6‑7” in the song **“Doot Doot (6 7)”** by Skrilla featuring G Herbo.  
- The phrase quickly became a catch‑all slang on TikTok and Instagram Reels, used for comedic edits, punchlines, and as a general hype tag.  
- A hand‑gesture mimicking the numbers 6 and 7 (the “67 Hand Sign”) grew out of the meme and spread as a visual shorthand for the trend.  

**2) Origin / Timeline**  
- **December 2024** – Skrilla releases “Doot Doot (6 7)”.  
- **Early 2025** – TikTok users latch onto the “6‑7” lyric; the meme spreads across short‑form video platforms.  
- **January 2025** – The song and its refrain go viral, cementing “6‑7” as a meme phrase.  
- **Late August 2025** – The “67 Hand Sign / 6 7 Handshake” emerges, popularized by TikTok videos that showcase the finger formation.  

**3) Sources**  
- https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/67-meme – explains meme’s lyric origin & viral spread.  
- https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/6-7_(meme) – outlines early‑2025 TikTok/Instagram rise.  
- https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/67-hand-sign-6-7-handshake – details hand‑sign development in Aug 2025.  
- https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doot_Doot_(6_7) – provides song background and numeric refrain’s meme impact.
